.Dd April 18, 2026
.Dt PROWLD 8
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm prowld
.Nd MidnightBSD service management daemon
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl d
.Op Fl s Ar rundir
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a dependency-aware, parallel-execution service manager for MidnightBSD.
It supersedes the traditional sequential
.Xr rc 8
startup model while maintaining full backward compatibility with existing
.Pa /etc/rc.d
scripts and the
.Xr service 8
command.
.Pp
.Nm
reads unit files from several directories, wraps legacy
.Xr rc.d 8
scripts as compatibility shims, builds a directed acyclic dependency graph,
and starts services in parallel based on dependency ordering.
It is typically started by
.Xr rc 8
early in the boot sequence and runs for the lifetime of the system.
.Pp
The following options are available:
.Bl -tag -width "-s rundir"
.It Fl d
Debug mode.
.Nm
runs in the foreground and writes log messages to standard error in
addition to
.Xr syslog 3 .
.It Fl s Ar rundir
Override the runtime state directory.
By default,
.Nm
uses
.Pa /var/run/prowld
for its control socket, PID file, and sd_notify sockets.
If that directory is not writable
.Po
for example, on read-only installation media
.Pc ,
.Nm
automatically falls back to
.Pa /tmp/prowld .
The
.Fl s
flag forces a specific directory regardless of writability.
All other runtime paths
.Pq notify socket directory, PID file, IPC socket, generated unit directory
are derived from
.Ar rundir .
.El
.Sh CONFIGURATION FILE
.Nm
reads daemon-level configuration from
.Pa /etc/prowld/prowld.conf
on startup and when
.Dv SIGHUP
is received.
The file is parsed by
.Xr libucl 3
and accepts UCL or JSON syntax.
The file must be owned by root and must not be world-writable;
.Nm
ignores it otherwise.
.Pp
The following keys are recognised:
.Bl -tag -width "max_concurrent_starts"
.It Va max_concurrent_starts
Maximum number of jobs that may be simultaneously transitioning to the
.Cm starting
state.
Accepts an integer greater than or equal to zero, or the string
.Dq auto .
Zero and
.Dq auto
both select the default of
.Va ncpu * 2 ,
with a floor of 4.
This limits parallelism during the startup wave without affecting the
number of already-running jobs.
.It Va shutdown_timeout
System-wide budget in seconds for orderly shutdown.
Services marked
.Va shutdown_wait: true
or with
.Dv KEYWORD: shutdown
receive graceful stop handling; if they do not exit within their individual
.Va exit_timeout ,
they are killed.
.Nm
waits for all such services to finish, up to
.Va shutdown_timeout
seconds total.
Default: 300.
.It Va debug
Boolean.
Enables debug logging to standard error.
The command-line
.Fl d
flag always takes precedence.
Default: false.
.El
.Pp
Example:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
max_concurrent_starts = auto
shutdown_timeout = 120
debug = false
.Ed
.Sh UNIT FILES
Unit files are parsed by
.Xr libucl 3
and accept UCL, JSON, or simplified YAML syntax.
Files must have the
.Pa .unit
extension.
.Pp
Unit file directories are searched in the following order;
a file at a higher-priority path with the same
.Va label
fully replaces the lower-priority file:
.Bl -enum -compact
.It
.Pa /etc/prowld/units.d/
.It
.Pa /usr/local/etc/prowld/units.d/
.It
.Pa /etc/prowld/overrides.d/
.It
.Pa /var/run/prowld/generated.d/
.Pq runtime-generated; follows Fl s Ar rundir
.El
.Pp
A minimal unit file:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
{
  "label": "org.midnightbsd.sshd",
  "description": "OpenSSH Daemon",
  "program": "/usr/sbin/sshd",
  "arguments": ["-D"],
  "run_at_load": true,
  "keep_alive": true
}
.Ed
.Ss Identity Fields
.Bl -tag -width "description"
.It Va label
.Pq required
Unique reverse-DNS identifier for the job,
for example
.Dq org.midnightbsd.sshd .
Must contain only alphanumerics, dots, hyphens, and underscores.
Must not begin with a dot or contain the sequence
.Dq .. .
.It Va description
Human-readable description string.
.It Va type
One of
.Cm daemon
(long-running process),
.Cm oneshot
(runs to completion and exits),
.Cm timer
(schedule-driven),
or
.Cm socket
(activated on first connection).
Default:
.Cm daemon .
.It Va rc_name
Variable prefix used in
.Pa /etc/rc.conf
for the
.Va _enable
flag.
Defaults to the last dot-separated component of
.Va label
.Pq e.g., Va org.midnightbsd.sshd No produces Va sshd_enable .
Set this explicitly to avoid collisions between units whose labels
would otherwise derive to the same name.
.El
.Ss Execution Fields
.Bl -tag -width "working_directory"
.It Va program
.Pq required unless Va arguments[0] is a full path
Absolute path to the executable.
.It Va arguments
Array of strings passed as
.Vt argv .
The executable name is prepended automatically as
.Vt argv[0] .
.It Va environment
Object of key/value pairs merged into the process environment.
The child process receives only the variables listed here; it does
not inherit
.Nm Ap s
own environment.
.It Va working_directory
Directory to
.Xr chdir 2
into before executing the program.
.It Va root_directory
Optional filesystem isolation boundary.
When set,
.Nm
calls
.Xr chroot 2
into this directory before dropping privileges and executing the program.
.Xr chdir 2
to
.Pa /
is performed immediately after
.Xr chroot 2
to ensure the process cannot access paths outside the new root via a
lingering working-directory reference.
.Va working_directory ,
if also set, is then interpreted relative to the chroot root.
.Xr chroot 2
is called as root and must succeed;
if it fails the service is not started.
Note that
.Xr chroot 2
alone is not a complete security sandbox:
a service running as root inside the chroot can still escape it.
Pair
.Va root_directory
with
.Va user
to drop privileges before the program runs.
.It Va user , Va group
Drop privileges to this user and group before
.Xr execve 2 .
Supplementary groups are set from the password database.
.It Va umask
Octal umask string applied before execution
.Pq e.g., Dq 0022 .
.El
.Ss Lifecycle Fields
.Bl -tag -width "throttle_interval"
.It Va run_at_load
If true, start the job automatically when it is loaded and all
dependencies are satisfied.
Default: false.
.It Va keep_alive
Boolean or object controlling the restart policy after the process exits.
.Pp
When set to
.Cm true ,
the job is always restarted regardless of exit status
(equivalent to
.Va { "always": true } ) .
.Pp
When set to an object, the following boolean keys are recognised:
.Bl -tag -width "successful_exit" -compact
.It Va always
Restart unconditionally.
.It Va crashed
Restart when the process exits with a non-zero status or is killed by a signal.
.It Va successful_exit
Restart even when the process exits cleanly with status 0.
.El
.It Va throttle_interval
Minimum seconds between restart attempts.
Prevents rapid restart loops after repeated failures.
Default: 10.
.It Va exit_timeout
Seconds to wait after
.Dv SIGTERM
before sending
.Dv SIGKILL
during stop or watchdog kill.
Default: 20.
.It Va shutdown_wait
If true, the job receives graceful shutdown handling during system shutdown:
.Nm
waits for it to exit before returning to init, bounded by
.Va shutdown_timeout
in
.Pa prowld.conf .
Equivalent to
.Dv KEYWORD: shutdown
in rc.d scripts.
Default: false.
.El
.Ss Dependency Fields
.Bl -tag -width "conflicts"
.It Va requires
Array of capability names that must be in the
.Cm running
or
.Cm completed
state before this job starts.
If a required dependency fails,
this job transitions to
.Cm failed .
Implies
.Va after .
.It Va wants
Like
.Va requires ,
but failure or absence of the dependency does not fail this job.
Implies
.Va after .
.It Va before
This job must be started before the listed jobs.
Adds a reverse dependency edge to those jobs.
.It Va after
This job must be started after the listed jobs.
.It Va conflicts
Array of job labels that cannot run while this job is running.
Starting this job stops the listed jobs.
.It Va provides
Array of capability names this job satisfies.
Other jobs depending on these names are unblocked when this job reaches
.Cm running .
.El
.Ss I/O Fields
.Bl -tag -width "standard_error_path"
.It Va standard_in_path
Path for standard input.
Defaults to
.Pa /dev/null .
.It Va standard_out_path
Path for standard output.
If unset, the job inherits the standard output of
.Nm .
.It Va standard_error_path
Path for standard error.
If unset, the job inherits the standard error of
.Nm .
.El
.Ss Resource Fields
.Bl -tag -width "resource_limits"
.It Va nice
Nice value applied via
.Xr setpriority 2
before execution.
Positive values lower priority; negative values raise it (root only).
Default: 0.
.It Va resource_limits
Object controlling
.Xr setrlimit 2
values.
Recognised keys:
.Bl -tag -width "max_processes" -compact
.It Va max_open_files
Maximum number of open file descriptors
.Pq Dv RLIMIT_NOFILE .
.It Va max_processes
Maximum number of processes
.Pq Dv RLIMIT_NPROC .
.El
.El
.Ss Notification Fields
.Bl -tag -width "watchdog_sec"
.It Va notify_type
Readiness notification protocol.
.Cm none
.Pq default :
the job is considered running after
.Va throttle_interval
seconds if its process is still alive.
.Cm notify :
the job must send
.Dv READY=1
on its sd_notify socket before
.Nm
marks it running; if
.Dv READY=1
is not received within
.Va exit_timeout
seconds the job is killed.
.It Va watchdog_sec
Watchdog interval in seconds.
When non-zero,
.Nm
sets
.Ev WATCHDOG_USEC
and
.Ev WATCHDOG_PID
in the job environment.
The job must send
.Dv WATCHDOG=1
at least once per interval or
.Nm
sends
.Dv SIGTERM
followed by
.Dv SIGKILL
after
.Va exit_timeout
seconds.
0 disables the watchdog.
Default: 0.
.El
.Ss Socket Activation Fields
The
.Va sockets
field is an object whose keys are logical socket names and whose values
describe the socket to bind.
See
.Sx SOCKET ACTIVATION
for details.
.Pp
Each socket entry recognises the following keys:
.Bl -tag -width "seqpacket"
.It Va type
Socket type:
.Cm stream
.Pq default, TCP-style ,
.Cm dgram
.Pq UDP-style ,
or
.Cm seqpacket .
.It Va path
Filesystem path for an
.Dv AF_UNIX
socket.
Mutually exclusive with
.Va port .
.It Va port
TCP or UDP port number for an
.Dv AF_INET
or
.Dv AF_INET6
socket.
.It Va host
Bind address for inet sockets.
If omitted,
.Nm
binds to all interfaces
.Pq Dv INADDR_ANY / Dv in6addr_any .
If the address contains a colon,
.Dv AF_INET6
is assumed; otherwise
.Dv AF_INET .
.It Va backlog
Listen backlog passed to
.Xr listen 2 .
0 uses
.Dv SOMAXCONN .
Ignored for datagram sockets.
Default: 0.
.El
.Sh SOCKET ACTIVATION
Jobs with a
.Va sockets
block are activated on demand.
.Nm
binds and listens on all configured sockets at load time, before the job
process is started.
When the first incoming connection or datagram arrives on any of the job's
sockets,
.Nm
fork/execs the job and passes the bound socket file descriptors starting at
fd 3 using the
.Ev LISTEN_FDS
protocol:
.Bl -tag -width "LISTEN_FDNAMES"
.It Ev LISTEN_FDS
Number of file descriptors passed, starting at fd 3.
.It Ev LISTEN_PID
PID of the process the descriptors were intended for.
Daemons should verify this matches their own PID.
.It Ev LISTEN_FDNAMES
Colon-separated list of logical socket names, in fd order.
Derived from the keys of the unit's
.Va sockets
block.
.El
.Pp
This protocol is wire-compatible with systemd socket activation, so daemons
built for Linux using
.Fn sd_listen_fds
work without modification.
.Pp
After the daemon exits,
.Nm
re-arms the socket watchers and waits for the next connection.
While waiting, the job is in the
.Cm running
state from the dependency scheduler's perspective, so dependent jobs
are not blocked.
.Sh READY NOTIFICATION
When
.Va notify_type
is set to
.Cm notify ,
.Nm
creates a Unix datagram socket at
.Pa /var/run/prowld/notify/<label>
before forking the job and sets
.Ev NOTIFY_SOCKET
in the child's environment.
The job signals readiness by sending a datagram containing
.Dv READY=1
to that socket.
.Pp
The following
.Dv KEY=value
pairs are recognised in notification datagrams:
.Bl -tag -width "EXTEND_TIMEOUT_USEC=n"
.It Dv READY=1
Mark the job as running.
Cancels the readiness timeout timer.
.It Dv STATUS=text
Set a human-readable status line shown by
.Xr prowlctl 8
.Cm status .
.It Dv MAINPID=pid
Update the tracked main PID.
Useful for daemons that double-fork after sending
.Dv READY=1 .
The value is accepted only if all three of the following conditions hold:
.Bl -enum -compact
.It
The candidate PID exists in the kernel process table.
.It
Its effective UID matches the user the job was configured to run as
(or root when no
.Cm user
is specified).
.It
It is a descendant of the currently tracked service PID,
verified by walking the parent-PID chain via
.Xr sysctl 3 .
.El
A value that fails any check is rejected and logged at
.Dv LOG_WARNING ;
the previously tracked PID is left unchanged.
This prevents a compromised service from redirecting
.Nm Ap s
stop and watchdog signals onto unrelated processes.
.It Dv WATCHDOG=1
Reset the watchdog timer.
.It Dv RELOADING=1
Log that the service is reloading configuration.
.It Dv STOPPING=1
Log that the service is shutting down.
.It Dv ERRNO=n
Log a startup error code.
.It Dv EXTEND_TIMEOUT_USEC=n
Extend the current readiness timeout by
.Ar n
microseconds.
.El
.Pp
Unknown keys are silently ignored for forward compatibility.
.Sh BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY
All existing scripts in
.Pa /etc/rc.d
and
.Pa /usr/local/etc/rc.d
are automatically discovered and wrapped as compatibility shim jobs.
The
.Dv REQUIRE ,
.Dv PROVIDE ,
.Dv BEFORE ,
and
.Dv KEYWORD
headers are parsed and translated into
.Nm
dependency fields.
.Pp
Enable state is read from
.Pa /etc/rc.conf
using the
.Va <name>_enable
variable, exactly as
.Xr rc.subr 8
does.
A service with
.Va foo_enable=NO
is loaded and appears in
.Xr prowlctl 8
output but is not started.
.Pp
If a native unit file and an
.Pa rc.d
script both claim the same
.Va provides ,
the native unit wins and the
.Pa rc.d
script is skipped.
This allows incremental migration: shipping a native unit file
automatically retires the rc.d script without any administrator action.
.Sh READ-ONLY MEDIA
.Nm
is designed to operate correctly on read-only installation media
.Pq CD-ROMs, read-only USB flash
and in early-boot environments where
.Pa /var
is not yet writable.
.Pp
If the runtime directory
.Pq Pa /var/run/prowld by default
cannot be created,
.Nm
automatically falls back to
.Pa /tmp/prowld ,
which is typically backed by a memory filesystem.
All derived paths
.Pq IPC socket, PID file, sd_notify sockets, generated unit directory
are rebuilt under the fallback root.
The
.Fl s Ar rundir
flag forces a specific root without triggering auto-detection.
.Pp
If the IPC socket cannot be bound,
.Nm
logs a warning and continues operating without the management socket.
Service management proceeds normally;
.Xr prowlctl 8
commands are unavailable until the socket becomes accessible.
.Pp
If
.Nm
is executed as PID 1
.Pq i.e., Fn getpid returns 1 ,
.Xr daemon 3
is not called, and debug output is forced to standard error.
When the main event loop exits, the system is halted via
.Fn reboot RB_HALT
rather than returning from
.Fn main ,
since PID 1 must never exit.
.Sh SIGNALS
.Bl -tag -width "SIGTERM"
.It Dv SIGTERM , Dv SIGINT
Begin an orderly shutdown.
All managed services are stopped
.Pq graceful for those marked Va shutdown_wait ,
forced for others.
When all services have exited,
.Nm
itself exits.
.It Dv SIGHUP
Reload configuration.
.Nm
re-reads
.Pa prowld.conf ,
rescans all unit directories, rescans the rc.d directories, rebuilds the
dependency graph, and schedules any newly eligible jobs.
Running jobs are not interrupted.
.It Dv SIGCHLD
Reap all available child processes.
.Nm
uses
.Fn waitpid -1 ... WNOHANG
in a loop; no action is required from the administrator.
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width "/var/run/prowld/generated.d/" -compact
.It Pa /etc/prowld/prowld.conf
Daemon configuration file.
.It Pa /etc/prowld/units.d/
Base system unit files (do not edit; use overrides.d).
.It Pa /usr/local/etc/prowld/units.d/
Ports and packages unit files.
.It Pa /etc/prowld/overrides.d/
Local administrator overrides.
.It Pa /var/run/prowld/
Runtime state directory.
Replaced by
.Pa /tmp/prowld
on read-only media or when
.Fl s
is given.
.It Pa /var/run/prowld/prowld.sock
Control socket
.Pq Unix domain, mode 0660, owned root:wheel .
.It Pa /var/run/prowld/prowld.pid
PID file.
.It Pa /var/run/prowld/notify/
Per-job sd_notify datagram sockets
.Pq mode 0700 .
.It Pa /var/run/prowld/generated.d/
Runtime-generated unit files
.Pq e.g., from prowl-generator .
.It Pa /var/db/prowld/masked.d/
Symlinks to
.Pa /dev/null
for masked services.
Each symlink is named after the job's label.
.It Pa /var/log/prowld/
.Nm
own log directory.
.It Pa /var/log/prowld/jobs/
Per-job log files
.Pq mode 0750 .
.It Pa /etc/rc.conf
Authoritative source for service enable state.
.El
.Sh DIAGNOSTICS
.Nm
logs to
.Xr syslog 3
under the
.Dv LOG_DAEMON
facility.
With
.Fl d ,
messages are also written to standard error.
.Pp
A job that fails to start repeatedly is placed in the
.Cm failed
state and is not restarted unless
.Cm keep_alive
is configured.
Use
.Xr prowlctl 8
.Cm status
to inspect the last exit code.
.Pp
Cycle detection runs at load time.
A job involved in a dependency cycle is placed in the
.Cm failed
state and logged at
.Dv LOG_ERR .
The system continues booting without the affected services.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr kqueue 2 ,
.Xr prowlctl 8 ,
.Xr rc 8 ,
.Xr rc.conf 5 ,
.Xr rcorder 8 ,
.Xr service 8 ,
.Xr syslog 3 ,
.Xr sysrc 8
.Sh HISTORY
.Nm
first appeared in MidnightBSD 4.1.
